Hi,

The error indicates that you have passed a filepath in `C:/Users/schakr01/Desktop/NRG/voxelmorph/voxelmorph/data/` with files that do not match how our data was organized. Originally, our data is organized in npz files, each of which has  'vol_data' variable with the volume in it. However, the data generator also handles other files (like nifti). Can you tell me what type of files you have?

Thanks!

After pulling the repo, I didn't modify the data folder so it has the original structure. It looks like this:
![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/38768265/48663871-082f2b80-ea5c-11e8-8e7d-d3f94559a0f3.png)
Do I need to make any modifications in the folder?

We should be more clear -- the path you pass as the first argument to train should have all your subjects that you want to align. The `voxelmorph/data/` folder is simply folder that includes data users might want to play with (e.g. the atlas, the labels we use, and an example subject). 

If you'd like to train voxelmorph to work for a population, you need more images. But to get started, here's a quick thing you can do: copy `test_vol.npz` to some general data folder, and then pass that folder to voxelmorph, and the `voxelmorph/data/atlas_norm.npz` as the atlas. This should work.

Hi Adrian,

Thank you for the clarification. I copied the test_vol.npz to a different folder, used the atlas and am running this now:
`train_miccai2018.py C:/Users/schakr01/Desktop/NRG/voxelmorph/voxelmorph/test_data --atlas_file C:/Users/schakr01/Desktop/NRG/voxelmorph/voxelmorph/data/atlas_norm.npz --gpu 0 --model_dir C:/Users/schakr01/Desktop/NRG/voxelmorph/voxelmorph/models`

hi @satrajitgithub 

Sorry, just to be clear -- you are just trying to register two images? The code above indicated that you are training a model, which requires a bunch of data and really requires a GPU to be efficient.

registration is much simpler, and should take about a minute on a cpu. All you need for this is to read in a model, and run `model.predict(ref, image)`. I am happy to provide a python script for this if you need.
Hi Adrian. It'll be great if you can provide the script. Thank you so much!

Hi @adalca 
It will be great if you can provide the script for running the registration.

@satrajitgithub apologies for the delay on this
I'm trying to write a robust script for people to use, but we have been travelling for a bit. Script should be up soon.  Did you try simple loading the model `model.load_weights` and then running `model.predict(ref, image)` ? This should do the trick for a quick experiment.
Hi @adalca I will try doing that. Thanks!
@satrajitgithub sorry about the delay. I've updated a rudimentary `register.py` in the `src` folder.

Hi adalca:
    When I run the train.py, I also encountered the problem mentioned above.(KeyError: 'vol_data is not a file in the archive').You said copy `test_vol.npz` to some general data folder, and then pass that folder to voxelmorph, and the `voxelmorph/data/atlas_norm.npz` as the atlas. This should work.But I don't know how to do this.So could you please send me the code and data after your change? I am looking forward to your reply.

Hi,

Can you tell me which part you don't know how to do? 

Here's what I am suggesting:
1. move `test_vol.npz` to `/some/path/wherever`
2. Then run train simply as: `train_miccai2018.py /some/path/wherever --atlas_file ../data/atlas_norm.npz`

This should work, I think.
